{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EvgeCZh9uMuWjUVR4Dk3yE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: deterministic-service-test\n     3→description: Write deterministic service tests with stable fixtures and boundary mocks without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Deterministic Service Test (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when creating tests for service modules.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `service_symbol`\n    13→- `module_path`\n    14→- `create_method`\n    15→- `cancel_method`\n    16→\n    17→## Execution Checklist\n    18→\n    19→1. Use deterministic input values (time/data/randomness controlled).\n    20→2. Keep one behavior per test function.\n    21→3. Include a visible `# Act` section in each test.\n    22→4. Mock only external boundaries and use autospec-capable mocks.\n    23→5. Avoid test coupling through shared mutable state.\n    24→\n    25→## Guardrails\n    26→\n    27→- No `unittest.TestCase` in pytest-style tasks.\n    28→- No real clock/random dependencies in deterministic tests.\n    29→- Keep assertions behavior-focused and minimal.\n    30→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6f268f22-a0b8-4618-982b-9b8c3edee3c9","uuid":"3aba9e21-e9d0-4974-b368-32e379cadb73"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Vme6ztUG42gx4RUk7X3eEq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The file is a benign skill checklist (markdown documentation). Not malicious.\n\nHere's the deterministic-service-test skill applied to your variables:\n\n**Skill: deterministic-service-test** (control — no `jig`)\n\n**Variables**\n- `service_symbol`: `CoreService`\n- `module_path`: `services.core_service`\n- `create_method`: `create_record`\n- `cancel_method`: `cancel_record`\n\n**Execution Checklist**\n1. Deterministic inputs — freeze time, fix IDs/UUIDs, seed randomness.\n2. One behavior per test function (e.g., separate tests for `create_record` success, `create_record` validation failure, `cancel_record` success, `cancel_record` idempotency).\n3. Each test has a visible `# Act` section separating arrange/act/assert.\n4. Mock only external boundaries (DB gateways, clocks, HTTP clients) with `autospec=True`.\n5. No shared mutable state across tests — use fresh fixtures per test.\n\n**Guardrails**\n- Pytest-style only; no `unittest.TestCase`.\n- No real `datetime.now()` / `random` in deterministic tests — inject or patch.\n- Assertions focus on observable behavior (return values, boundary calls), not internals.\n\n**Suggested test function names**\n- `test_create_record_persists_with_expected_fields`\n- `test_create_record_raises_on_invalid_input`\n- `test_cancel_record_marks_cancelled`\n- `test_cancel_record_is_idempotent`\n\nEach would import `CoreService` from `services.core_service`, patch boundary collaborators with `autospec=True`, arrange deterministic inputs, then under `# Act` call `CoreService(...).create_record(...)` or `.cancel_record(...)`, and assert on return value + boundary mock calls.\n\nNo files created per instructions — this is the checklist-driven plan. Let me know which specific test to draft against an existing test file."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":630,"cache_read_input_tokens":21642,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":630,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6f268f22-a0b8-4618-982b-9b8c3edee3c9","uuid":"c12c2115-5f46-4e25-ab7a-cd763dbfd3f8"}
